I 240X  Imperial Britain and the World Wars  1900 50  pending approval for the X designation for both courses and the W for the ERH course at this time  Students will visit several significant historical sites in and around London  such as Bletchley Park  Shakespeare s Globe Theater  and the University of Oxford  In addition to literary and historical studies  classroom time will be combined with on site research in various museums  including the British Museum  Imperial War Museum  and the Victoria   Albert Museum  Students will apply classroom discussions and readings to these on site visits to write enriched field trip reports and research essays on the First and Second World Wars in an imperial context  Program Director LTC Pennie Ticen earned her Ph D  at the University of Massachusetts  Amherst  She enjoys teaching classes on modernism and post colonial literature   Her current research centers on the use of the essay by post colonial writers such as Chinua Achebe and Salman Rushdie  MAJ John Matsui received his Ph D  at the Johns Hopkins University  He enjoys teaching courses on the American Civil War and the Atlantic World  In 2013 and 2014  MAJ Matsui received VMI Grants in Aid of Scholarship to further his research on missionaries and Empire in London   He is writing a book on religion and empire in an Anglo American context Home   Academics   Programs   International Programs   Study Abroad   Summer in London Home   Academics   Programs   International Programs   Study Abroad   Summer in London Home Academics Programs International Programs Study Abroad      London The Virginia Military Institute  in partnership with the Richmond  The American International University in London  is pleased to present a summer four week cultural immersion program in London to study the history and literature of Great Britain during the two World Wars  Dates  May 19   June 16  2016 Costs   6600 plus airfare and most meals subject to BOV approval Fees include tuition  insura